{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":1000,"text":"I'm supposed to scare you, because it's about fear, right?"},{"time":5000,"text":"And you should be really afraid,"},{"time":7000,"text":"but not for the reasons why you think you should be."},{"time":10000,"text":"You should be really afraid that --"},{"time":12000,"text":"if we stick up the first slide on this thing -- there we go -- that you're missing out."},{"time":18000,"text":"Because if you spend this week thinking about Iraq and"},{"time":22000,"text":"thinking about Bush and thinking about the stock market,"},{"time":26000,"text":"you're going to miss one of the greatest adventures that we've ever been on."},{"time":29000,"text":"And this is what this adventure's really about."},{"time":31000,"text":"This is crystallized DNA."},{"time":35000,"text":"Every life form on this planet -- every insect, every bacteria, every plant,"},{"time":38000,"text":"every animal, every human, every politician -- (Laughter)"},{"time":43000,"text":"is coded in that stuff."},{"time":45000,"text":"And if you want to take a single crystal of DNA, it looks like that."},{"time":49000,"text":"And we're just beginning to understand this stuff."},{"time":52000,"text":"And this is the single most exciting adventure that we have ever been on."},{"time":56000,"text":"It's the single greatest mapping project we've ever been on."},{"time":59000,"text":"If you think that the mapping of America's made a difference,"},{"time":61000,"text":"or landing on the moon, or this other stuff,"},{"time":64000,"text":"it's the map of ourselves and the map of every plant"},{"time":67000,"text":"and every insect and every bacteria that really makes a difference."},{"time":70000,"text":"And it's beginning to tell us a lot about evolution."},{"time":75000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":79000,"text":"It turns out that what this stuff is --"},{"time":81000,"text":"and Richard Dawkins has written about this --"},{"time":83000,"text":"is, this is really a river out of Eden."},{"time":85000,"text":"So, the 3.2 billion base pairs inside each of your cells"},{"time":89000,"text":"is really a history of where you've been for the past billion years."},{"time":92000,"text":"And we could start dating things,"},{"time":93000,"text":"and we could start changing medicine and archeology."},{"time":97000,"text":"It turns out that if you take the human species about 700 years ago,"},{"time":100000,"text":"white Europeans diverged from black Africans in a very significant way."},{"time":103000,"text":"White Europeans were subject to the plague."},{"time":109000,"text":"And when they were subject to the plague, most people didn't survive,"},{"time":112000,"text":"but those who survived had a mutation on the CCR5 receptor."},{"time":116000,"text":"And that mutation was passed on to their kids"},{"time":118000,"text":"because they're the ones that survived,"},{"time":120000,"text":"so there was a great deal of population pressure."},{"time":122000,"text":"In Africa, because you didn't have these cities,"},{"time":124000,"text":"you didn't have that CCR5 population pressure mutation."},{"time":127000,"text":"We can date it to 700 years ago."},{"time":130000,"text":"That is one of the reasons why AIDS is raging across Africa as fast as it is,"},{"time":134000,"text":"and not as fast across Europe."},{"time":138000,"text":"And we're beginning to find these little things for malaria,"},{"time":141000,"text":"for sickle cell, for cancers."},{"time":145000,"text":"And in the measure that we map ourselves,"},{"time":147000,"text":"this is the single greatest adventure that we'll ever be on."},{"time":149000,"text":"And this Friday, I want you to pull out a really good bottle of wine,"},{"time":153000,"text":"and I want you to toast these two people."},{"time":156000,"text":"Because this Friday, 50 years ago, Watson and Crick found the structure of DNA,"},{"time":160000,"text":"and that is almost as important a date"},{"time":163000,"text":"as the 12th of February when we first mapped ourselves,"},{"time":166000,"text":"but anyway, we'll get to that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":168000,"text":"I thought we'd talk about the new zoo."},{"time":170000,"text":"So, all you guys have heard about DNA, all the stuff that DNA does,"},{"time":174000,"text":"but some of the stuff we're discovering is kind of nifty"},{"time":177000,"text":"because this turns out to be the single most abundant species on the planet."},{"time":182000,"text":"If you think you're successful or cockroaches are successful,"},{"time":185000,"text":"it turns out that there's ten trillion trillion Pleurococcus sitting out there."},{"time":188000,"text":"And we didn't know that Pleurococcus was out there,"},{"time":191000,"text":"which is part of the reason"},{"time":192000,"text":"why this whole species-mapping project is so important."},{"time":197000,"text":"Because we're just beginning to learn"},{"time":199000,"text":"where we came from and what we are."},{"time":201000,"text":"And we're finding amoebas like this. This is the amoeba dubia."},{"time":205000,"text":"And the amoeba dubia doesn't look like much,"},{"time":207000,"text":"except that each of you has about 3.2 billion letters,"},{"time":210000,"text":"which is what makes you you,"},{"time":212000,"text":"as far as gene code inside each of your cells,"},{"time":215000,"text":"and this little amoeba which, you know,"},{"time":218000,"text":"sits in water in hundreds and millions and billions,"},{"time":221000,"text":"turns out to have 620 billion base pairs of gene code inside."},{"time":227000,"text":"So, this little thingamajig has a genome"},{"time":230000,"text":"that's 200 times the size of yours."},{"time":233000,"text":"And if you're thinking of efficient information storage mechanisms,"},{"time":237000,"text":"it may not turn out to be chips."},{"time":240000,"text":"It may turn out to be something that looks a little like that amoeba."}]},{"cues":[{"time":244000,"text":"And, again, we're learning from life and how life works."},{"time":248000,"text":"This funky little thing: people didn't used to think"},{"time":252000,"text":"that it was worth taking samples out of nuclear reactors"},{"time":255000,"text":"because it was dangerous and, of course, nothing lived there."},{"time":258000,"text":"And then finally somebody picked up a microscope"},{"time":261000,"text":"and looked at the water that was sitting next to the cores."},{"time":264000,"text":"And sitting next to that water in the cores"},{"time":266000,"text":"was this little Deinococcus radiodurans, doing a backstroke,"},{"time":269000,"text":"having its chromosomes blown apart every day,"},{"time":271000,"text":"six, seven times, restitching them,"},{"time":274000,"text":"living in about 200 times the radiation that would kill you."},{"time":277000,"text":"And by now you should be getting a hint as to how diverse"},{"time":280000,"text":"and how important and how interesting this journey into life is,"},{"time":282000,"text":"and how many different life forms there are,"},{"time":285000,"text":"and how there can be different life forms living in"},{"time":288000,"text":"very different places, maybe even outside of this planet."},{"time":292000,"text":"Because if you can live in radiation that looks like this,"},{"time":294000,"text":"that brings up a whole series of interesting questions."}]},{"cues":[{"time":298000,"text":"This little thingamajig: we didn't know this thingamajig existed."},{"time":302000,"text":"We should have known that this existed"},{"time":304000,"text":"because this is the only bacteria that you can see to the naked eye."},{"time":307000,"text":"So, this thing is 0.75 millimeters."},{"time":310000,"text":"It lives in a deep trench off the coast of Namibia."},{"time":313000,"text":"And what you're looking at with this namibiensis"},{"time":315000,"text":"is the biggest bacteria we've ever seen."},{"time":317000,"text":"So, it's about the size of a little period on a sentence."},{"time":321000,"text":"Again, we didn't know this thing was there three years ago."},{"time":325000,"text":"We're just beginning this journey of life in the new zoo."}]},{"cues":[{"time":329000,"text":"This is a really odd one. This is Ferroplasma."},{"time":333000,"text":"The reason why Ferroplasma is interesting is because it eats iron,"},{"time":337000,"text":"lives inside the equivalent of battery acid,"},{"time":341000,"text":"and excretes sulfuric acid."},{"time":345000,"text":"So, when you think of odd life forms,"},{"time":347000,"text":"when you think of what it takes to live,"},{"time":351000,"text":"it turns out this is a very efficient life form,"},{"time":353000,"text":"and they call it an archaea. Archaea means \"the ancient ones.\""},{"time":357000,"text":"And the reason why they're ancient is because this thing came up"},{"time":361000,"text":"when this planet was covered"},{"time":363000,"text":"by things like sulfuric acid in batteries,"},{"time":364000,"text":"and it was eating iron when the earth was part of a melted core."},{"time":369000,"text":"So, it's not just dogs and cats and whales and dolphins"},{"time":373000,"text":"that you should be aware of and interested in on this little journey."}]},{"cues":[{"time":377000,"text":"Your fear should be that you are not,"},{"time":380000,"text":"that you're paying attention to stuff which is temporal."},{"time":383000,"text":"I mean, George Bush -- he's going to be gone, alright? Life isn't."},{"time":389000,"text":"Whether the humans survive or don't survive,"},{"time":392000,"text":"these things are going to be living on this planet or other planets."},{"time":395000,"text":"And it's just beginning to understand this code of DNA"},{"time":399000,"text":"that's really the most exciting intellectual adventure"},{"time":402000,"text":"that we've ever been on."}]},{"cues":[{"time":405000,"text":"And you can do strange things with this stuff. This is a baby gaur."},{"time":409000,"text":"Conservation group gets together,"},{"time":411000,"text":"tries to figure out how to breed an animal that's almost extinct."},{"time":416000,"text":"They can't do it naturally, so what they do with this thing is"},{"time":419000,"text":"they take a spoon, take some cells out of an adult gaur's mouth, code,"},{"time":425000,"text":"take the cells from that and insert it into a fertilized cow's egg,"},{"time":430000,"text":"reprogram cow's egg -- different gene code."},{"time":434000,"text":"When you do that, the cow gives birth to a gaur."},{"time":439000,"text":"We are now experimenting with bongos, pandas, elands, Sumatran tigers,"},{"time":445000,"text":"and the Australians -- bless their hearts --"},{"time":448000,"text":"are playing with these things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":449000,"text":"Now, the last of these things died in September 1936."},{"time":453000,"text":"These are Tasmanian tigers. The last known one died at the Hobart Zoo."},{"time":457000,"text":"But it turns out that as we learn more about gene code"},{"time":460000,"text":"and how to reprogram species,"},{"time":462000,"text":"we may be able to close the gene gaps in deteriorate DNA."},{"time":467000,"text":"And when we learn how to close the gene gaps,"},{"time":470000,"text":"then we can put a full string of DNA together."},{"time":473000,"text":"And if we do that, and insert this into a fertilized wolf's egg,"},{"time":478000,"text":"we may give birth to an animal"},{"time":480000,"text":"that hasn't walked the earth since 1936."},{"time":483000,"text":"And then you can start going back further,"},{"time":485000,"text":"and you can start thinking about dodos,"},{"time":488000,"text":"and you can think about other species."},{"time":490000,"text":"And in other places, like Maryland, they're trying to figure out"},{"time":493000,"text":"what the primordial ancestor is."},{"time":495000,"text":"Because each of us contains our entire gene code"},{"time":498000,"text":"of where we've been for the past billion years,"},{"time":501000,"text":"because we've evolved from that stuff,"},{"time":503000,"text":"you can take that tree of life and collapse it back,"},{"time":505000,"text":"and in the measure that you learn to reprogram,"},{"time":508000,"text":"maybe we'll give birth to something"},{"time":510000,"text":"that is very close to the first primordial ooze."},{"time":512000,"text":"And it's all coming out of things that look like this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":514000,"text":"These are companies that didn't exist five years ago."},{"time":516000,"text":"Huge gene sequencing facilities the size of football fields."},{"time":520000,"text":"Some are public. Some are private."},{"time":522000,"text":"It takes about 5 billion dollars to sequence a human being the first time."},{"time":526000,"text":"Takes about 3 million dollars the second time."},{"time":528000,"text":"We will have a 1,000-dollar genome within the next five to eight years."},{"time":532000,"text":"That means each of you will contain on a CD your entire gene code."},{"time":537000,"text":"And it will be really boring. It will read like this."},{"time":540000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":542000,"text":"The really neat thing about this stuff is that's life."},{"time":544000,"text":"And Laurie's going to talk about this one a little bit."},{"time":547000,"text":"Because if you happen to find this one inside your body,"},{"time":549000,"text":"you're in big trouble, because that's the source code for Ebola."},{"time":553000,"text":"That's one of the deadliest diseases known to humans."},{"time":555000,"text":"But plants work the same way and insects work the same way,"},{"time":557000,"text":"and this apple works the same way."},{"time":559000,"text":"This apple is the same thing as this floppy disk."},{"time":561000,"text":"Because this thing codes ones and zeros,"},{"time":563000,"text":"and this thing codes A, T, C, Gs, and it sits up there,"},{"time":565000,"text":"absorbing energy on a tree, and one fine day"},{"time":568000,"text":"it has enough energy to say, execute, and it goes [thump]. Right?"},{"time":572000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":575000,"text":"And when it does that, pushes a .EXE, what it does is,"},{"time":579000,"text":"it executes the first line of code, which reads just like that,"},{"time":582000,"text":"AATCAGGGACCC, and that means: make a root."},{"time":585000,"text":"Next line of code: make a stem."},{"time":587000,"text":"Next line of code, TACGGGG: make a flower that's white,"},{"time":590000,"text":"that blooms in the spring, that smells like this."},{"time":593000,"text":"In the measure that you have the code"},{"time":595000,"text":"and the measure that you read it --"},{"time":598000,"text":"and, by the way, the first plant was read two years ago;"},{"time":600000,"text":"the first human was read two years ago;"},{"time":602000,"text":"the first insect was read two years ago."}]},{"cues":[{"time":604000,"text":"The first thing that we ever read was in 1995:"},{"time":607000,"text":"a little bacteria called Haemophilus influenzae."},{"time":610000,"text":"In the measure that you have the source code, as all of you know,"},{"time":613000,"text":"you can change the source code, and you can reprogram life forms"},{"time":615000,"text":"so that this little thingy becomes a vaccine,"},{"time":617000,"text":"or this little thingy starts producing biomaterials,"},{"time":620000,"text":"which is why DuPont is now growing a form of polyester"},{"time":623000,"text":"that feels like silk in corn."},{"time":626000,"text":"This changes all rules. This is life, but we're reprogramming it."},{"time":633000,"text":"This is what you look like. This is one of your chromosomes."},{"time":637000,"text":"And what you can do now is,"},{"time":639000,"text":"you can outlay exactly what your chromosome is,"},{"time":642000,"text":"and what the gene code on that chromosome is right here,"},{"time":645000,"text":"and what those genes code for, and what animals they code against,"},{"time":648000,"text":"and then you can tie it to the literature."},{"time":650000,"text":"And in the measure that you can do that, you can go home today,"},{"time":653000,"text":"and get on the Internet, and access"},{"time":655000,"text":"the world's biggest public library, which is a library of life."},{"time":659000,"text":"And you can do some pretty strange things"},{"time":661000,"text":"because in the same way as you can reprogram this apple,"},{"time":664000,"text":"if you go to Cliff Tabin's lab at the Harvard Medical School,"},{"time":667000,"text":"he's reprogramming chicken embryos to grow more wings."},{"time":673000,"text":"Why would Cliff be doing that? He doesn't have a restaurant."},{"time":676000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":678000,"text":"The reason why he's reprogramming that animal to have more wings"},{"time":681000,"text":"is because when you used to play with lizards as a little child,"},{"time":684000,"text":"and you picked up the lizard, sometimes the tail fell off, but it regrew."},{"time":688000,"text":"Not so in human beings:"},{"time":691000,"text":"you cut off an arm, you cut off a leg -- it doesn't regrow."},{"time":694000,"text":"But because each of your cells contains your entire gene code,"},{"time":699000,"text":"each cell can be reprogrammed, if we don't stop stem cell research"},{"time":703000,"text":"and if we don't stop genomic research,"},{"time":705000,"text":"to express different body functions."},{"time":709000,"text":"And in the measure that we learn how chickens grow wings,"},{"time":712000,"text":"and what the program is for those cells to differentiate,"},{"time":714000,"text":"one of the things we're going to be able to do"},{"time":717000,"text":"is to stop undifferentiated cells, which you know as cancer,"},{"time":721000,"text":"and one of the things we're going to learn how to do"},{"time":723000,"text":"is how to reprogram cells like stem cells"},{"time":726000,"text":"in such a way that they express bone, stomach, skin, pancreas."},{"time":733000,"text":"And you are likely to be wandering around -- and your children --"},{"time":736000,"text":"on regrown body parts in a reasonable period of time,"},{"time":740000,"text":"in some places in the world where they don't stop the research."}]},{"cues":[{"time":745000,"text":"How's this stuff work? If each of you differs"},{"time":750000,"text":"from the person next to you by one in a thousand, but only three percent codes,"},{"time":753000,"text":"which means it's only one in a thousand times three percent,"},{"time":755000,"text":"very small differences in expression and punctuation"},{"time":758000,"text":"can make a significant difference. Take a simple declarative sentence."},{"time":763000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":765000,"text":"Right?"},{"time":766000,"text":"That's perfectly clear. So, men read that sentence,"},{"time":770000,"text":"and they look at that sentence, and they read this."},{"time":778000,"text":"Okay?"},{"time":779000,"text":"Now, women look at that sentence and they say, uh-uh, wrong."},{"time":783000,"text":"This is the way it should be seen."},{"time":787000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":795000,"text":"That's what your genes are doing."},{"time":796000,"text":"That's why you differ from this person over here by one in a thousand."},{"time":801000,"text":"Right? But, you know, he's reasonably good looking, but..."},{"time":804000,"text":"I won't go there."},{"time":807000,"text":"You can do this stuff even without changing the punctuation."},{"time":811000,"text":"You can look at this, right?"},{"time":815000,"text":"And they look at the world a little differently."},{"time":817000,"text":"They look at the same world and they say..."},{"time":819000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":825000,"text":"That's how the same gene code -- that's why you have 30,000 genes,"},{"time":829000,"text":"mice have 30,000 genes, husbands have 30,000 genes."},{"time":832000,"text":"Mice and men are the same. Wives know that, but anyway."},{"time":836000,"text":"You can make very small changes in gene code"},{"time":838000,"text":"and get really different outcomes,"},{"time":842000,"text":"even with the same string of letters."},{"time":846000,"text":"That's what your genes are doing every day."},{"time":849000,"text":"That's why sometimes a person's genes"},{"time":851000,"text":"don't have to change a lot to get cancer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":857000,"text":"These little chippies, these things are the size of a credit card."},{"time":862000,"text":"They will test any one of you for 60,000 genetic conditions."},{"time":865000,"text":"That brings up questions of privacy and insurability"},{"time":868000,"text":"and all kinds of stuff, but it also allows us to start going after diseases,"},{"time":871000,"text":"because if you run a person who has leukemia through something like this,"},{"time":875000,"text":"it turns out that three diseases with"},{"time":877000,"text":"completely similar clinical syndromes"},{"time":881000,"text":"are completely different diseases."},{"time":883000,"text":"Because in ALL leukemia, that set of genes over there over-expresses."},{"time":886000,"text":"In MLL, it's the middle set of genes,"},{"time":888000,"text":"and in AML, it's the bottom set of genes."},{"time":890000,"text":"And if one of those particular things is expressing in your body,"},{"time":895000,"text":"then you take Gleevec and you're cured."},{"time":898000,"text":"If it is not expressing in your body,"},{"time":900000,"text":"if you don't have one of those types --"},{"time":902000,"text":"a particular one of those types -- don't take Gleevec."},{"time":905000,"text":"It won't do anything for you."},{"time":907000,"text":"Same thing with Receptin if you've got breast cancer."},{"time":910000,"text":"Don't have an HER-2 receptor? Don't take Receptin."},{"time":913000,"text":"Changes the nature of medicine. Changes the predictions of medicine."},{"time":917000,"text":"Changes the way medicine works."}]},{"cues":[{"time":919000,"text":"The greatest repository of knowledge when most of us went to college"},{"time":922000,"text":"was this thing, and it turns out that"},{"time":924000,"text":"this is not so important any more."},{"time":926000,"text":"The U.S. Library of Congress, in terms of its printed volume of data,"},{"time":930000,"text":"contains less data than is coming out of a good genomics company"},{"time":934000,"text":"every month on a compound basis."},{"time":937000,"text":"Let me say that again: A single genomics company"},{"time":940000,"text":"generates more data in a month, on a compound basis,"},{"time":943000,"text":"than is in the printed collections of the Library of Congress."},{"time":947000,"text":"This is what's been powering the U.S. economy. It's Moore's Law."},{"time":951000,"text":"So, all of you know that the price of computers halves every 18 months"},{"time":956000,"text":"and the power doubles, right?"},{"time":958000,"text":"Except that when you lay that side by side with the speed"},{"time":962000,"text":"with which gene data's being deposited in GenBank,"},{"time":965000,"text":"Moore's Law is right here: it's the blue line."},{"time":970000,"text":"This is on a log scale, and that's what superexponential growth means."},{"time":974000,"text":"This is going to push computers to have to grow faster"},{"time":978000,"text":"than they've been growing, because so far,"},{"time":980000,"text":"there haven't been applications that have been required"},{"time":983000,"text":"that need to go faster than Moore's Law. This stuff does."}]},{"cues":[{"time":986000,"text":"And here's an interesting map."},{"time":988000,"text":"This is a map which was finished at the Harvard Business School."},{"time":992000,"text":"One of the really interesting questions is, if all this data's free,"},{"time":995000,"text":"who's using it? This is the greatest public library in the world."},{"time":999000,"text":"Well, it turns out that there's about 27 trillion bits"},{"time":1002000,"text":"moving inside from the United States to the United States;"},{"time":1005000,"text":"about 4.6 trillion is going over to those European countries;"},{"time":1009000,"text":"about 5.5's going to Japan; there's almost no communication"},{"time":1012000,"text":"between Japan, and nobody else is literate in this stuff."},{"time":1016000,"text":"It's free. No one's reading it. They're focusing on the war;"},{"time":1021000,"text":"they're focusing on Bush; they're not interested in life."},{"time":1024000,"text":"So, this is what a new map of the world looks like."},{"time":1027000,"text":"That is the genomically literate world. And that is a problem."},{"time":1033000,"text":"In fact, it's not a genomically literate world."},{"time":1035000,"text":"You can break this out by states."},{"time":1037000,"text":"And you can watch states rise and fall depending on"},{"time":1039000,"text":"their ability to speak a language of life,"},{"time":1041000,"text":"and you can watch New York fall off a cliff,"},{"time":1043000,"text":"and you can watch New Jersey fall off a cliff,"},{"time":1045000,"text":"and you can watch the rise of the new empires of intelligence."},{"time":1049000,"text":"And you can break it out by counties, because it's specific counties."},{"time":1052000,"text":"And if you want to get more specific,"},{"time":1054000,"text":"it's actually specific zip codes."},{"time":1056000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1058000,"text":"So, you want to know where life is happening?"},{"time":1061000,"text":"Well, in Southern California it's happening in 92121. And that's it."},{"time":1067000,"text":"And that's the triangle between Salk, Scripps, UCSD,"},{"time":1072000,"text":"and it's called Torrey Pines Road."},{"time":1074000,"text":"That means you don't need to be a big nation to be successful;"},{"time":1077000,"text":"it means you don't need a lot of people to be successful;"},{"time":1079000,"text":"and it means you can move most of the wealth of a country"},{"time":1082000,"text":"in about three or four carefully picked 747s."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1086000,"text":"Same thing in Massachusetts. Looks more spread out but --"},{"time":1090000,"text":"oh, by the way, the ones that are the same color are contiguous."},{"time":1094000,"text":"What's the net effect of this?"},{"time":1096000,"text":"In an agricultural society, the difference between"},{"time":1098000,"text":"the richest and the poorest,"},{"time":1100000,"text":"the most productive and the least productive, was five to one. Why?"},{"time":1104000,"text":"Because in agriculture, if you had 10 kids"},{"time":1106000,"text":"and you grow up a little bit earlier and you work a little bit harder,"},{"time":1109000,"text":"you could produce about five times more wealth, on average,"},{"time":1111000,"text":"than your neighbor."},{"time":1113000,"text":"In a knowledge society, that number is now 427 to 1."},{"time":1117000,"text":"It really matters if you're literate, not just in reading and writing"},{"time":1121000,"text":"in English and French and German,"},{"time":1123000,"text":"but in Microsoft and Linux and Apple."},{"time":1126000,"text":"And very soon it's going to matter if you're literate in life code."},{"time":1130000,"text":"So, if there is something you should fear,"},{"time":1132000,"text":"it's that you're not keeping your eye on the ball."},{"time":1135000,"text":"Because it really matters who speaks life."},{"time":1138000,"text":"That's why nations rise and fall."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1141000,"text":"And it turns out that if you went back to the 1870s,"},{"time":1144000,"text":"the most productive nation on earth was Australia, per person."},{"time":1147000,"text":"And New Zealand was way up there. And then the U.S. came in about 1950,"},{"time":1150000,"text":"and then Switzerland about 1973, and then the U.S. got back on top --"},{"time":1154000,"text":"beat up their chocolates and cuckoo clocks."},{"time":1158000,"text":"And today, of course, you all know that the most productive nation"},{"time":1161000,"text":"on earth is Luxembourg, producing about one third more wealth"},{"time":1164000,"text":"per person per year than America."},{"time":1167000,"text":"Tiny landlocked state. No oil. No diamonds. No natural resources."},{"time":1171000,"text":"Just smart people moving bits. Different rules."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1177000,"text":"Here's differential productivity rates."},{"time":1181000,"text":"Here's how many people it takes to produce a single U.S. patent."},{"time":1184000,"text":"So, about 3,000 Americans, 6,000 Koreans, 14,000 Brits,"},{"time":1188000,"text":"790,000 Argentines. You want to know why Argentina's crashing?"},{"time":1191000,"text":"It's got nothing to do with inflation."},{"time":1193000,"text":"It's got nothing to do with privatization."},{"time":1195000,"text":"You can take a Harvard-educated Ivy League economist,"},{"time":1199000,"text":"stick him in charge of Argentina. He still crashes the country"},{"time":1202000,"text":"because he doesn't understand how the rules have changed."},{"time":1205000,"text":"Oh, yeah, and it takes about 5.6 million Indians."},{"time":1208000,"text":"Well, watch what happens to India."},{"time":1210000,"text":"India and China used to be 40 percent of the global economy"},{"time":1213000,"text":"just at the Industrial Revolution, and they are now about 4.8 percent."},{"time":1218000,"text":"Two billion people. One third of the global population producing 5 percent of the wealth"},{"time":1222000,"text":"because they didn't get this change,"},{"time":1225000,"text":"because they kept treating their people like serfs"},{"time":1227000,"text":"instead of like shareholders of a common project."},{"time":1231000,"text":"They didn't keep the people who were educated."},{"time":1234000,"text":"They didn't foment the businesses. They didn't do the IPOs."},{"time":1237000,"text":"Silicon Valley did. And that's why they say"},{"time":1241000,"text":"that Silicon Valley has been powered by ICs."},{"time":1244000,"text":"Not integrated circuits: Indians and Chinese."},{"time":1247000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1251000,"text":"Here's what's happening in the world."},{"time":1253000,"text":"It turns out that if you'd gone to the U.N. in 1950,"},{"time":1256000,"text":"when it was founded, there were 50 countries in this world."},{"time":1258000,"text":"It turns out there's now about 192."},{"time":1261000,"text":"Country after country is splitting, seceding, succeeding, failing --"},{"time":1266000,"text":"and it's all getting very fragmented. And this has not stopped."},{"time":1271000,"text":"In the 1990s, these are sovereign states"},{"time":1274000,"text":"that did not exist before 1990."},{"time":1276000,"text":"And this doesn't include fusions or name changes or changes in flags."},{"time":1281000,"text":"We're generating about 3.12 states per year."},{"time":1284000,"text":"People are taking control of their own states,"},{"time":1287000,"text":"sometimes for the better and sometimes for the worse."},{"time":1290000,"text":"And the really interesting thing is,"},{"time":1292000,"text":"you and your kids are empowered to build great empires,"},{"time":1294000,"text":"and you don't need a lot to do it."},{"time":1296000,"text":"(Music)"},{"time":1298000,"text":"And, given that the music is over, I was going to talk"},{"time":1301000,"text":"about how you can use this to generate a lot of wealth,"},{"time":1304000,"text":"and how code works."},{"time":1306000,"text":"Moderator: Two minutes."},{"time":1307000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":1309000,"text":"Juan Enriquez: No, I'm going to stop there and we'll do it next year"},{"time":1313000,"text":"because I don't want to take any of Laurie's time."},{"time":1316000,"text":"But thank you very much."}]}]}